  <md:title>The Standard Normal Distribution</md:title>
  <md:abstract>This module introduces standard normal distribution and standardizing the distribution.</md:abstract>
  <md:uuid>c65d2401-7b2c-4ce3-962b-d7ef29fc156b</md:uuid>
</metadata>

<content>
    <para id="intro">As previously discussed, normal distributions
      do not necessarily have the same means and standard
      deviations. A normal distribution with a mean of 0 and a
      standard deviation of 1 is called a <term target-id="standard">standard normal distribution</term>
      and is typically represented by <m:math><m:ci>Z</m:ci> </m:math>.
    </para><para id="tablestandard">Areas underneath the normal distribution are often represented by tables
      of the standard normal distribution. A portion of a table of the
      standard normal distribution is shown in <link target-id="standardtable"/>.
    </para><table id="standardtable" frame="all" summary="Table of areas to the left of Z."><title>A portion of a table of the standard normal distribution.</title>
<tgroup cols="2" colsep="1" rowsep="1"><thead>
	  <row>
	    <entry>Z</entry>
	    <entry>Area left of Z</entry>
	  </row>
